ucial historiographical developments; present different professions that have gained new attention in the context of an emerging Global Labour History; critically engage the boundaries of "free" labour and the ambiguities contained in this concept; and take up and historicize current debates about "informal labour". Global Histories of Work will familiarize readers with a burgeoning fi eld of high academic, social, and political relevance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aLaborxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aStanziani, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLichtenstein, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLüdtke, Alf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckert, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Vito, Christian G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckert, Andreas , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBalachandran, G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpittler, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyslop, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeeks, Kathie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalt, Lucien van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinden, Marcel van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenning, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonner, Philip, 